# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: envelope-encryption
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:envelope-encryption/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] A cryptographic key is a string of data that is used to lock or unlock cryptographic functions, including authentication, authorization and encryption.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Cryptographic keys are grouped into **cryptographic key types** according to the functions they perform.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Consider a keyring that contains a variety of keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] These keys might be various shapes and sizes, but one thing is certain, each will generally serve a separate purpose.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] One key might be used to start an automobile, while another might be used to open a safe deposit box.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] The automobile key will not work to open the safe deposit box and vice versa.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] This analogy provides some insight on how cryptographic key types work.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] These keys are categorized in respect to how they are used and what properties they possess.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] A cryptographic key is categorized according to how it will be used and what properties it has.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] For example, a key might have one of the following properties: Symmetric, Public or Private.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Keys may also be grouped into pairs that have one private and one public key, which is referred to as an Asymmetric key pair.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Asymmetric keys differ from symmetric keys in that the algorithms use separate keys for encryption and decryption, while a symmetric key’s algorithm uses a single key for both processes.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Because multiple keys are used with an asymmetric algorithm, the process takes longer to produce than a symmetric key algorithm would.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] However, the benefits lay in the fact that an asymmetric algorithm is much more secure than a symmetric key algorithm is.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] With a symmetric key, the key needs to be transmitted to the receiver, where there is always the possibility that the key could be intercepted or tampered with.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] With an asymmetric key, the message and/or accompanying data can be sent or received by using a public key; however, the receiver or sender would use his or her personal private key to access the message and/or accompanying data.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Thus, asymmetric keys are suited for use for transmitting confidential messages and data and when authentication is required for assurance that the message has not been tampered with.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Only the receiver, who is in possession of the private key corresponding to the public key(encryption only key), has the ability to decode the message.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] A public key can be sent back and forth between recipients, but a private key remains fixed to one location and is not sent back and forth, which keeps it safe from being intercepted during transmission.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Cryptographic keys may also have keys that designate they can be used for long-term (static, archived) use or used for a single session (ephemeral).
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] The latter generally applies to the use of an Ephemeral Key Agreement Key.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Most other key types are designed to last for long crypto-periods, from about one to two years.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] When a shorter crypto-period is designed different key types may be used, such as Data Encryption keys, Symmetric Authentication keys, Private Key-Transport keys, Key-Wrapping keys, Authorization keys or RNG keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] This page shows the classification of key types from the point of view of key management.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] In a key management system, each key should be labeled with one such type and that key should never be used for a different purpose.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] ) key pairs that are used by public key algorithms to generate digital signatures with possible long-term implications.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] A public signature verification key is the public key of an asymmetric key pair that is used by a public key algorithm to verify digital signatures, either to authenticate a user's identity, to determine the integrity of the data, for non-repudiation, or a combination thereof.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] authentication keys are used with symmetric key algorithms to provide assurance of the integrity and source of messages, communication sessions, or stored data.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] A private authentication key is the private key of an asymmetric key pair that is used with a public key algorithm to provide assurance as to the integrity of information, and the identity of the originating entity or the source of messages, communication sessions, or stored data.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] A public authentication key is the public key of an asymmetric key pair that is used with a public key algorithm to determine the integrity of information and to authenticate the identity of entities, or the source of messages, communication sessions, or stored data.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] These keys are used with symmetric key algorithms to apply confidentiality protection to information.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Symmetric key wrapping keys are used to encrypt other keys using symmetric key algorithms.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Key wrapping keys are also known as key encrypting keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] A symmetric master key is used to derive other symmetric keys (e.g., data encryption keys, key wrapping keys, or authentication keys) using symmetric cryptographic methods.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Private key transport keys are the private keys of asymmetric key pairs that are used to decrypt keys that have been encrypted with the associated public key using a public key algorithm.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Public key transport keys are the public keys of asymmetric key pairs that are used to encrypt keys using a public key algorithm.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] These keys are used to establish keys (e.g., key wrapping keys, data encryption keys or MAC keys) and, optionally, other keying material (e.g., Initialization Vectors).
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] These symmetric keys are used to establish keys (e.g., key wrapping keys, data encryption keys, or MAC keys) and, optionally, other keying material (e.g., Initialization Vectors) using a symmetric key agreement algorithm.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] agreement keys are the private keys of asymmetric key pairs that are used to establish keys (e.g., key wrapping keys, data encryption keys, or MAC keys) and, optionally, other keying material (e.g., Initialization Vectors).
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Public static key agreement keys are the public keys of asymmetric key pairs that are used to establish keys (e.g., key wrapping keys, data encryption keys, or MAC keys) and, optionally, other keying material (e.g., Initialization Vectors).
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] agreement keys are the private keys of asymmetric key pairs that are used only once to establish one or more keys (e.g., key wrapping keys, data encryption keys, or MAC keys) and, optionally, other keying material (e.g., Initialization Vectors).
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] Public ephemeral key agreement keys are the public keys of asymmetric key pairs that are used in a single key establishment transaction to establish one or more keys (e.g., key wrapping keys, data encryption keys, or MAC keys) and, optionally, other keying material (e.g., Initialization Vectors).
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] keys are used to provide privileges to an entity using a symmetric cryptographic method.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] The authorization key is known by the entity responsible for monitoring and granting access privileges for authorized entities and by the entity seeking access to resources.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] A private authorization key is the private key of an asymmetric key pair that is used to provide privileges to an entity.
[src:envelope-encryption/cryptographic-key-types] A public authorization key is the public key of an asymmetric key pair that is used to verify privileges for an entity that knows the associated private authorization key.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] In cryptography, **encryption** (more specifically, encoding) is the process of transforming information in a way that, ideally, only authorized parties can decode.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] This process converts the original representation of the information, known as plaintext, into an alternative form known as ciphertext.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Despite its goal, encryption does not itself prevent interference but denies the intelligible content to a would-be interceptor.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] For technical reasons, an encryption scheme usually uses a pseudo-random encryption key generated by an algorithm.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] It is possible to decrypt the message without possessing the key but, for a well-designed encryption scheme, considerable computational resources and skills are required.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] An authorized recipient can easily decrypt the message with the key provided by the originator to recipients but not to unauthorized users.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Historically, various forms of encryption have been used to aid in cryptography.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Early encryption techniques were often used in military messaging.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Since then, new techniques have emerged and become commonplace in all areas of modern computing.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Modern encryption schemes use the concepts of public-key and symmetric-key.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Modern encryption techniques ensure security because modern computers are inefficient at cracking the encryption.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] One of the earliest forms of encryption is symbol replacement, which was first found in the tomb of Khnumhotep II, who lived in 1900 BC Egypt.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Symbol replacement encryption is "non-standard," which means that the symbols require a cipher or key to understand.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] This type of early encryption was used throughout Ancient Greece and Rome for military purposes.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] One of the most famous military encryption developments was the Caesar cipher, in which a plaintext letter is shifted a fixed number of positions along the alphabet to get the encoded letter.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] A message encoded with this type of encryption could be decoded with a fixed number on the Caesar cipher.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Around 800 AD, Arab mathematician al-Kindi developed the technique of frequency analysis – which was an attempt to crack ciphers systematically, including the Caesar cipher.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] This technique looked at the frequency of letters in the encrypted message to determine the appropriate shift: for example, the most common letter in English text is E and is therefore likely to be represented by the letter that appears most commonly in the ciphertext.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] This technique was rendered ineffective by the polyalphabetic cipher, described by al-Qalqashandi (1355–1418) and Leon Battista Alberti (in 1465), which varied the substitution alphabet as encryption proceeded in order to confound such analysis.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Around 1790, Thomas Jefferson theorized a cipher to encode and decode messages to provide a more secure way of military correspondence.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The cipher, known today as the Wheel Cipher or the Jefferson Disk, although never actually built, was theorized as a spool that could jumble an English message up to 36 characters.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The message could be decrypted by plugging in the jumbled message to a receiver with an identical cipher.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] A similar device to the Jefferson Disk, the M-94, was developed in 1917 independently by US Army Major Joseph Mauborne.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] This device was used in U.S. military communications until 1942.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] In World War II, the Axis powers used a more advanced version of the M-94 called the Enigma Machine.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The Enigma Machine was more complex because unlike the Jefferson Wheel and the M-94, each day the jumble of letters switched to a completely new combination.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Each day's combination was only known by the Axis, so many thought the only way to break the code would be to try over 17,000 combinations within 24 hours.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The Allies used computing power to severely limit the number of reasonable combinations they needed to check every day, leading to the breaking of the Enigma Machine.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Today, encryption is used in the transfer of communication over the Internet for security and commerce.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] As computing power continues to increase, computer encryption is constantly evolving to prevent eavesdropping attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] One of the first "modern" cipher suites, DES, used a 56-bit key with 72,057,594,037,927,936 possibilities; it was cracked in 1999 by EFF's brute-force DES cracker, which required 22 hours and 15 minutes to do so.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Modern encryption standards often use stronger key sizes, such as AES (256-bit mode), TwoFish, ChaCha20-Poly1305, Serpent (configurable up to 512-bit).
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Cipher suites that use a 128-bit or higher key, like AES, cannot be brute-forced because the total number of keys is 3.4028237e+38 possibilities.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The most likely option for cracking ciphers with large key sizes is to find vulnerabilities in the cipher itself, like inherent biases and backdoors or by exploiting physical side effects through Side-channel attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] For example, RC4, a stream cipher, was cracked due to inherent biases and vulnerabilities in the cipher.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] In the context of cryptography, encryption serves as a mechanism to ensure confidentiality.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Since data may be visible on the Internet, sensitive information such as passwords and personal communication may be exposed to potential interceptors.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The process of encrypting and decrypting messages involves keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The two main types of keys in cryptographic systems are symmetric-key and public-key (also known as asymmetric-key).
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Many complex cryptographic algorithms often use simple modular arithmetic in their implementations.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] In symmetric-key schemes, the encryption and decryption keys are the same.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Communicating parties must have the same key in order to achieve secure communication.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The German Enigma Machine used a new symmetric-key each day for encoding and decoding messages.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] In public-key cryptography schemes, the encryption key is published for anyone to use and encrypt messages.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] However, only the receiving party has access to the decryption key that enables messages to be read.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Public-key encryption was first described in a secret document in 1973; beforehand, all encryption schemes were symmetric-key (also called private-key).
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Although published subsequently, the work of Diffie and Hellman was published in a journal with a large readership, and the value of the methodology was explicitly described.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The method became known as the Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] RSA (Rivest–Shamir–Adleman) is another notable public-key cryptosystem.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Created in 1978, it is still used today for applications involving digital signatures.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Using number theory, the RSA algorithm selects two prime numbers, which help generate both the encryption and decryption keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] A publicly available public-key encryption application called Pretty Good Privacy (PGP) was written in 1991 by Phil Zimmermann, and distributed free of charge with source code.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] PGP was purchased by Symantec in 2010 and is regularly updated.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Encryption has long been used by militaries and governments to facilitate secret communication.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] It is now commonly used in protecting information within many kinds of civilian systems.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] For example, the Computer Security Institute reported that in 2007, 71% of companies surveyed used encryption for some of their data in transit, and 53% used encryption for some of their data in storage.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Encryption can be used to protect data "at rest", such as information stored on computers and storage devices (e.g.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] In recent years, there have been numerous reports of confidential data, such as customers' personal records, being exposed through loss or theft of laptops or backup drives; encrypting such files at rest helps protect them if physical security measures fail.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Digital rights management systems, which prevent unauthorized use or reproduction of copyrighted material and protect software against reverse engineering (see also copy protection), is another somewhat different example of using encryption on data at rest.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Encryption is also used to protect data in transit, for example data being transferred via networks (e.g. the Internet, e-commerce), mobile telephones, wireless microphones, wireless intercom systems, Bluetooth devices and bank automatic teller machines.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] There have been numerous reports of data in transit being intercepted in recent years.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Data should also be encrypted when transmitted across networks in order to protect against eavesdropping of network traffic by unauthorized users.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Encryption plays a central role in meeting regulatory requirements for the protection of sensitive data.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Under the HIPAA Security Rule, encryption of electronic protected health information (ePHI) is classified as an "addressable" implementation specification, meaning covered entities must implement it or document why an equivalent alternative measure is reasonable and appropriate.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Notably, the HIPAA Breach Notification Rule provides a safe harbor for encrypted data: breaches involving ePHI that has been encrypted in accordance with NIST standards are not considered reportable breaches.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would make encryption of ePHI at rest and in transit a mandatory requirement, removing its current "addressable" status.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires encryption of cardholder data both in storage (Requirement 3) and during transmission over open public networks (Requirement 4), specifying the use of strong cryptographic algorithms.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Conventional methods for permanently deleting data from a storage device involve overwriting the device's whole content with zeros, ones, or other patterns – a process which can take a significant amount of time, depending on the capacity and the type of storage medium.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Cryptography offers a way of making the erasure almost instantaneous.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] An example implementation of this method can be found on iOS devices, where the cryptographic key is kept in a dedicated 'effaceable storage'.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Because the key is stored on the same device, this setup on its own does not offer full privacy or security protection if an unauthorized person gains physical access to the device.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Encryption is used in the 21st century to protect digital data and information systems.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] As computing power increased over the years, encryption technology has only become more advanced and secure.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] However, this advancement in technology has also exposed a potential limitation of today's encryption methods.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The length of the encryption key is an indicator of the strength of the encryption method.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] For example, the original encryption key, DES (Data Encryption Standard), was 56 bits, meaning it had 2^56 combination possibilities.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] With today's computing power, a 56-bit key is no longer secure, being vulnerable to brute force attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Quantum computing uses properties of quantum mechanics in order to process large amounts of data simultaneously.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Quantum computing has been found to achieve computing speeds thousands of times faster than today's supercomputers.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] This computing power presents a challenge to today's encryption technology.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] For example, RSA encryption uses the multiplication of very large prime numbers to create a semiprime number for its public key.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Decoding this key without its private key requires this semiprime number to be factored, which can take a very long time to do with modern computers.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] It would take a supercomputer anywhere between weeks to months to factor in this key.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] However, quantum computing can use quantum algorithms to factor this semiprime number in the same amount of time it takes for normal computers to generate it.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] This would make all data protected by current public-key encryption vulnerable to quantum computing attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Other encryption techniques like elliptic curve cryptography and symmetric key encryption are also vulnerable to quantum computing.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] While quantum computing could be a threat to encryption security in the future, quantum computing as it currently stands is still very limited.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Quantum computing currently is not commercially available, cannot handle large amounts of code, and only exists as computational devices, not computers.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Furthermore, quantum computing advancements will be able to be used in favor of encryption as well.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The National Security Agency (NSA) is currently preparing post-quantum encryption standards for the future.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Quantum encryption promises a level of security that will be able to counter the threat of quantum computing.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Encryption is an important tool but is not sufficient alone to ensure the security or privacy of sensitive information throughout its lifetime.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Most applications of encryption protect information only at rest or in transit, leaving sensitive data in clear text and potentially vulnerable to improper disclosure during processing, such as by a cloud service for example.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Homomorphic encryption and secure multi-party computation are emerging techniques to compute encrypted data; these techniques are general and Turing complete but incur high computational and/or communication costs.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] In response to encryption of data at rest, cyber-adversaries have developed new types of attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] These more recent threats to encryption of data at rest include cryptographic attacks, stolen ciphertext attacks, attacks on encryption keys, insider attacks, data corruption or integrity attacks, data destruction attacks, and ransomware attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Data fragmentation and active defense data protection technologies attempt to counter some of these attacks, by distributing, moving, or mutating ciphertext so it is more difficult to identify, steal, corrupt, or destroy.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The question of balancing the need for national security with the right to privacy has been debated for years, since encryption has become critical in today's digital society.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The modern encryption debate started around the '90s when US government tried to ban cryptography because, according to them, it would threaten national security.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The debate is polarized around two opposing views.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Those who see strong encryption as a problem making it easier for criminals to hide their illegal acts online and others who argue that encryption keep digital communications safe.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The debate heated up in 2014, when Big Tech like Apple and Google set encryption by default in their devices.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] This was the start of a series of controversies that puts governments, companies and internet users at stake.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Authenticated encryption algorithms are designed to provide both encryption and integrity protection together.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Standards for cryptographic software and hardware to perform encryption are widely available, but successfully using encryption to ensure security may be a challenging problem.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] A single error in system design or execution can allow successful attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Sometimes an adversary can obtain unencrypted information without directly undoing the encryption.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] See for example traffic analysis, TEMPEST, or Trojan horse.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Encrypting at the time of creation is only secure if the encryption device itself has correct keys and has not been tampered with.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] If an endpoint device has been configured to trust a root certificate that an attacker controls, for example, then the attacker can both inspect and tamper with encrypted data by performing a man-in-the-middle attack anywhere along the message's path.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] The common practice of TLS interception by network operators represents a controlled and institutionally sanctioned form of such an attack, but countries have also attempted to employ such attacks as a form of control and censorship.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Even when encryption effectively conceals a message’s content and prevents tampering, the *length* of the ciphertext remains a form of metadata that can leak sensitive information.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] For instance, the well-known CRIME and BREACH attacks against HTTPS exploited information leakage through encrypted message length as a side-channel attack.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Traffic analysis more broadly refers to techniques that use metadata—such as message size and timing—to infer information about communication patterns.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Applying padding to a message before encryption can help obscure its true plaintext length, though this increases the ciphertext size and adds bandwidth overhead.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Padding may be applied randomly or deterministically, each approach involving different trade-offs.
[src:envelope-encryption/encryption] Encrypting and padding data to produce padded uniform random blobs (PURBs) ensures that the ciphertext reveals no metadata about the plaintext’s structure, leaking only asymptotically minimal $O(\log \log M)$ information through its length.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] This Key Management Cheat Sheet provides developers with guidance for implementation of cryptographic key management within an application in a secure manner.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Formulate a plan for the overall organization's cryptographic strategy to guide developers working on different applications and ensure that each application's cryptographic capability meets minimum requirements and best practices.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Identify the cryptographic and key management requirements for your application and map all components that process or store cryptographic key material.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Selection of the cryptographic and key management algorithms to use within a given application should begin with an understanding of the objectives of the application.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] For example, if the application is required to store data securely, then the developer should select an algorithm suite that supports the objective of data at rest protection security.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Applications that are required to transmit and receive data would select an algorithm suite that supports the objective of data in transit protection.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] We have provided recommendations on the selection of crypto suites within an application based on application and security objectives.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Application developers oftentimes begin the development of crypto and key management capabilities by examining what is available in a library.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] However, an analysis of the real needs of the application should be conducted to determine the optimal key management approach.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Begin by understanding the security objectives of the application which will then drive the selection of cryptographic protocols that are best suited.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Keys to create the data encryption keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Once the understanding of the security needs of the application is achieved, developers can determine what protocols and algorithms are required.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Once the protocols and algorithms are understood, you can begin to define the different types of keys that will support the application's objectives.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] **Authentication of End Devices:** Pre-shared symmetric keys, Trusted certificates, Trust Anchors.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] **Integrity Protection:** Message Authentication Codes (MACs).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] According to `NIST SP 800-57 Part 1`, many algorithms and schemes that provide a security service use a hash function as a component of the algorithm.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Hash functions can be found in digital signature algorithms (`FIPS186`), Keyed-Hash Message Authentication Codes (HMAC) (`FIPS198`), key-derivation functions/methods (`NIST Special Publications (SP) 800-56A, 800-56B, 800-56C and 800-108`), and random number generators (`NIST SP 800-90A`).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Approved hash functions are defined in `FIPS180`.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] `NIST SP 800-57 Part 1` recognizes three basic classes of approved cryptographic algorithms: hash functions, symmetric- key algorithms and asymmetric-key algorithms.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] The classes are defined by the number of cryptographic keys that are used in conjunction with the algorithm.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] The NSA released a report, Commercial National Security Algorithm Suite 2.0 which lists the cryptographic algorithms that are expected to be remain strong even with advances in quantum computing.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Cryptographic hash functions do not require keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Hash functions generate a relatively small digest (hash value) from a (possibly) large input in a way that is fundamentally difficult to reverse (i.e., it is hard to find an input that will produce a given output).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] To compress messages for digital signature generation and verification (Section 4.2.4).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] To derive keys in key-establishment algorithms (Section 4.2.5).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] To generate deterministic random numbers (Section 4.2.7).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Symmetric-key algorithms (sometimes known as secret-key algorithms) transform data in a way that is fundamentally difficult to undo without knowledge of a secret key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] The key is "symmetric" because the same key is used for a cryptographic operation and its inverse (e.g., encryption and decryption).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Symmetric keys are often known by more than one entity; however, the key shall not be disclosed to entities that are not authorized access to the data protected by that algorithm and key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] To provide authentication and integrity services (Section 4.2.3) in the form of Message Authentication Codes (MACs); the same key is used to generate the MAC and to validate it.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] MACs normally employ either a symmetric key-encryption algorithm or a cryptographic hash function as their cryptographic primitive.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] As part of the key-establishment process (Section 4.2.5).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Asymmetric-key algorithms, commonly known as public-key algorithms, use two related keys (i.e., a key pair) to perform their functions: a public key and a private key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] The public key may be known by anyone; the private key should be under the sole control of the entity that "owns" the key pair.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Even though the public and private keys of a key pair are related, knowledge of the public key does not reveal the private key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] To establish cryptographic keying material (Section 4.2.5).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] To generate random numbers (Section 4.2.7).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Message Authentication Codes (MACs) provide data authentication and integrity.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] A MAC is a cryptographic checksum on the data that is used in order to provide assurance that the data has not changed and that the MAC was computed by the expected entity.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Although message integrity is often provided using non-cryptographic techniques known as error detection codes, these codes can be altered by an adversary to effect an action to the adversary's benefit.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] The use of an approved cryptographic mechanism, such as a MAC, can alleviate this problem.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] In addition, the MAC can provide a recipient with assurance that the originator of the data is a key holder (i.e., an entity authorized to have the key).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] MACs are often used to authenticate the originator to the recipient when only those two parties share the MAC key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Digital signatures are used to provide authentication, integrity and non-repudiation.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Digital signatures are used in conjunction with hash functions and are computed on data of any length (up to a limit that is determined by the hash function).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] `FIPS186` specifies algorithms that are approved for the computation of digital signatures.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Symmetric key-wrapping keys are used to encrypt other keys using symmetric-key algorithms.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Key-wrapping keys are also known as key encrypting keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Review `NIST SP 800-57` (Recommendation for Key Management) for recommended guidelines on key strength for specific algorithm implementations.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] When encrypting keys for storage or distribution, always encrypt a cryptographic key with another key of equal or greater cryptographic strength.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] When moving to Elliptic Curve-based algorithms, choose a key length that meets or exceeds the comparative strength of other algorithms in use within your system.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Formulate a strategy for the overall organization's cryptographic strategy to guide developers working on different applications and ensure that each application's cryptographic capability meets minimum requirements and best practices.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Keys stored in memory for a long time can become "burned in".
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] This can be mitigated by splitting the key into components that are frequently updated.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Loss or corruption of the memory media on which keys and/or certificates are stored, and recovery planning, according to `NIST SP 800-57`.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Plan for the recovery from possible corruption of the memory media necessary for key or certificate generation, registration, and/or distribution systems, subsystems, or components as recommended in `NIST SP 800-57`.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Ephemeral keys can provide perfect forward secrecy protection, which means a compromise of the server's long term signing key does not compromise the confidentiality of past sessions.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] According to NIST, in general, a single key should be used for only one purpose (e.g., encryption, authentication, key wrapping, random number generation, or digital signatures).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Limiting the use of a key limits the damage that could be done if the key is compromised.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Some uses of keys interfere with each other.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] For example, the length of time the key may be required for each use and purpose.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Retention requirements of the data may differ for different data types.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] According to `NIST SP 800-133`, cryptographic modules are the set of hardware, software, and/or firmware that implements security functions (including cryptographic algorithms and key generation) and is contained within a cryptographic module boundary to provide protection of the keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Cryptographic keys shall be generated within cryptographic module with at least a `FIPS 140-2 or 140-3` compliance.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] For explanatory purposes, consider the cryptographic module in which a key is generated to be the key-generating module.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Any random value required by the key-generating module shall be generated within that module; that is, the Random Bit Generator that generates the random value shall be implemented within cryptographic module with at least a `FIPS 140-2 or 140-3` compliance that generates the key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Hardware cryptographic modules are preferred over software cryptographic modules for protection.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] The generated keys shall be transported (when necessary) using secure channels and shall be used by their associated cryptographic algorithm within at least a `FIPS 140-2 or 140-3` compliant cryptographic modules.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] For additional detail for the recommendations in this section refer to `NIST Special Paper 800-133`.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Keys must be protected on both volatile and persistent memory, ideally processed within secure cryptographic modules.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Keys should never be stored in plaintext format.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Ensure all keys are stored in a cryptographic vault, such as a hardware security module (HSM) or isolated cryptographic service.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] If you are planning on storing keys in offline devices/databases, then encrypt the keys using Key Encryption Keys (KEKs) prior to the export of the key material.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] KEK length (and algorithm) should be equivalent to or greater in strength than the keys being protected.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Ensure that keys have integrity protections applied while in storage (consider dual purpose algorithms that support encryption and Message Code Authentication (MAC)).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Ensure that standard application level code never reads or uses cryptographic keys in any way and use key management libraries.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Ensure that keys and cryptographic operation is done inside the sealed vault.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] All work should be done in the vault (such as key access, encryption, decryption, signing, etc).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] For a more complete guide to storing sensitive information such as keys, see the Secrets Management Cheat Sheet.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Data that has been encrypted with lost cryptographic keys will never be recovered.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Therefore, it is essential that the application incorporate a secure key backup capability, especially for applications that support data at rest encryption for long-term data stores.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] When backing up keys, ensure that the database that is used to store the keys is encrypted using at least a `FIPS 140-2 or 140-3` validated module.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] It is sometimes useful to escrow key material for use in investigations and for re-provisioning of key material to users in the event that the key is lost or corrupted.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Never escrow keys used for performing digital signatures, but consider the need to escrow keys that support encryption.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Oftentimes, escrow can be performed by the Certificate Authority (CA) or key management system that provisions certificates and keys, however in some instances separate APIs must be implemented to allow the system to perform the escrow for the application.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Accountability involves the identification of those that have access to, or control of, cryptographic keys throughout their lifecycles.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Accountability can be an effective tool to help prevent key compromises and to reduce the impact of compromises once they are detected.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Although it is preferred that no humans are able to view keys, as a minimum, the key management system should account for all individuals who are able to view plaintext cryptographic keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] In addition, more sophisticated key-management systems may account for all individuals authorized to access or control any cryptographic keys, whether in plaintext or ciphertext form.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] It tends to protect against compromise, because individuals with access to the key know that their access to the key is known.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] It is very useful in recovering from a detected key compromise to know where the key was used and what data or other keys were protected by the compromised key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Certain principles have been found to be useful in enforcing the accountability of cryptographic keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] These principles might not apply to all systems or all types of keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Identifying the dates and times of key use, along with the data that is protected.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Identifying other keys that are protected by a symmetric or private key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] The protective mechanisms employed should be periodically reassessed with respect to the level of security that they provide and are expected to provide in the future, and that the mechanisms correctly and effectively support the appropriate policies.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] New technology developments and attacks should be taken into consideration.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] On a more frequent basis, the actions of the humans that use, operate and maintain the system should be reviewed to verify that the humans continue to follow established security procedures.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Strong cryptographic systems can be compromised by lax and inappropriate human actions.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Highly unusual events should be noted and reviewed as possible indicators of attempted attacks on the system.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] A compromise of the integrity of a key means that the key is incorrect - either that the key has been modified (either deliberately or accidentally), or that another key has been substituted; this includes a deletion (non-availability) of the key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] The substitution or modification of a key used to provide integrity calls into question the integrity of all information protected by the key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] This information could have been provided by, or changed by, an unauthorized entity that knows the key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] The substitution of a public or secret key that will be used (at a later time) to encrypt data could allow an unauthorized entity (who knows the decryption key) to decrypt data that was encrypted using the encryption key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] A compromise of a key's usage or application association means that the key could be used for the wrong purpose (e.g., for key establishment instead of digital signatures) or for the wrong application, and could result in the compromise of information protected by the key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] A compromise of a key's association with the owner or other entity means that the identity of the other entity cannot be assured (i.e., one does not know who the other entity really is) or that information cannot be processed correctly (e.g., decrypted with the correct key).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] A compromise of a key's association with other information means that there is no association at all, or the association is with the wrong "information".
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] This could cause the cryptographic services to fail, information to be lost, or the security of the information to be compromised.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Certain protective measures may be taken in order to minimize the likelihood or consequences of a key compromise.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Similar affect as ransomware, except that you can't pay the ransom and get the key back.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Preventing humans from viewing plaintext symmetric and private keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Restricting plaintext symmetric and private keys to physically protected containers.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] This includes key generators, key-transport devices, key loaders, cryptographic modules, and key-storage devices.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Using integrity checks to ensure that the integrity of a key or its association with other data has not been compromised.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] For example, keys may be wrapped (i.e., encrypted) in such a manner that unauthorized modifications to the wrapping or to the associations will be detected.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Employing key confirmation (see NIST SP 800-57 Part 1 Section 4.2.5.5) to help ensure that the proper key was, in fact, established.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Establishing an accountability system that keeps track of each access to symmetric and private keys in plaintext form.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Providing a cryptographic integrity check on the key (e.g., using a MAC or a digital signature).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] The use of trusted timestamps for signed data. i.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Destroying keys as soon as they are no longer needed.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Creating a compromise-recovery plan, especially in the case of a CA compromise.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] A compromise-recovery plan is essential for restoring cryptographic security services in the event of a key compromise.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] A compromise-recovery plan shall be documented and easily accessible.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] The identification and contact info of the personnel to perform the recovery actions.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] An inventory of all cryptographic keys and their use (e.g., the location of all certificates in a system).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] The education of all appropriate personnel on the recovery procedures.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] An identification and contact info of all personnel needed to support the recovery procedures.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Policies that key-revocation checking be enforced (to minimize the effect of a compromise).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] The monitoring of the re-keying operations (to ensure that all required operations are performed for all affected keys).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Identification of all information that may be compromised as a result of the incident.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Identification of all signatures that may be invalid, due to the compromise of a signing key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Distribution of new keying material, if required.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Implement integrity controls on objects stored in the trust store.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Do not allow for export of keys held within the trust store without authentication and authorization.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Setup strict policies and procedures for exporting key material from applications to network applications and other components.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Implement a secure process for updating the trust store.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management-cheat-sheet] Use only reputable crypto libraries that are well maintained and updated, as well as tested and validated by third-party organizations (e.g., `NIST`/`FIPS`).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Key management concerns keys at the user level, either between users or systems.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] This is in contrast to key scheduling, which typically refers to the internal handling of keys within the operation of a cipher.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Successful key management is critical to the security of a cryptosystem.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Cryptographic systems may use different types of keys, with some systems using more than one.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] These may include symmetric keys or asymmetric keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] In a symmetric key algorithm the keys involved are identical for both encrypting and decrypting a message.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Keys must be chosen carefully, and distributed and stored securely.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Asymmetric keys, also known as public keys, in contrast are two distinct keys that are mathematically linked.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] They are typically used together to communicate.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Public key infrastructure (PKI), the implementation of public key cryptography, requires an organization to establish an infrastructure to create and manage public and private key pairs along with digital certificates.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] The starting point in any certificate and private key management strategy is to create a comprehensive inventory of all certificates, their locations and responsible parties.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] This is not a trivial matter because certificates from a variety of sources are deployed in a variety of locations by different individuals and teams - it's simply not possible to rely on a list from a single certificate authority.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Certificates that are not renewed and replaced before they expire can cause serious downtime and outages.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Once keys are inventoried, key management typically consists of three steps: exchange, storage and use.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Prior to any secured communication, users must set up the details of the cryptography.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] In some instances this may require exchanging identical keys (in the case of a symmetric key system).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] In others it may require possessing the other party's public key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] While public keys can be openly exchanged (their corresponding private key is kept secret), symmetric keys must be exchanged over a secure communication channel.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Formerly, exchange of such a key was extremely troublesome, and was greatly eased by access to secure channels such as a diplomatic bag.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Clear text exchange of symmetric keys would enable any interceptor to immediately learn the key, and any encrypted data.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] The advance of public key cryptography in the 1970s has made the exchange of keys less troublesome.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Since the Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol was published in 1975, it has become possible to exchange a key over an insecure communications channel, which has substantially reduced the risk of key disclosure during distribution.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] It is possible, using something akin to a book code, to include key indicators as clear text attached to an encrypted message.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] The encryption technique used by Richard Sorge's code clerk was of this type, referring to a page in a statistical manual, though it was in fact a code.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] The German Army Enigma symmetric encryption key was a mixed type early in its use; the key was a combination of secretly distributed key schedules and a user chosen session key component for each message.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] In more modern systems, such as OpenPGP compatible systems, a session key for a symmetric key algorithm is distributed encrypted by an asymmetric key algorithm.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] This approach avoids even the necessity for using a key exchange protocol like Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Another method of key exchange involves encapsulating one key within another.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Typically a master key is generated and exchanged using some secure method.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] This method is usually cumbersome or expensive (breaking a master key into multiple parts and sending each with a trusted courier for example) and not suitable for use on a larger scale.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Once the master key has been securely exchanged, it can then be used to securely exchange subsequent keys with ease.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] This technique is usually termed key wrap.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] A common technique uses block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] A related method is to exchange a master key (sometimes termed a root key) and derive subsidiary keys as needed from that key and some other data (often referred to as diversification data).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] The most common use for this method is probably in smartcard-based cryptosystems, such as those found in banking cards.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] The bank or credit network embeds their secret key into the card's secure key storage during card production at a secured production facility.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Then at the point of sale the card and card reader are both able to derive a common set of session keys based on the shared secret key and card-specific data (such as the card serial number).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] This method can also be used when keys must be related to each other (i.e., departmental keys are tied to divisional keys, and individual keys tied to departmental keys).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] However, tying keys to each other in this way increases the damage which may result from a security breach as attackers will learn something about more than one key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] This reduces entropy, with regard to an attacker, for each key involved.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] A recent method uses an oblivious pseudorandom function to issue keys without the key management system ever being in a position to see the keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] However distributed, keys must be stored securely to maintain communications security.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Security is a big concern and hence there are various techniques in use to do so.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Likely the most common is that an encryption application manages keys for the user and depends on an access password to control use of the key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Likewise, in the case of smartphone keyless access platforms, they keep all identifying door information off mobile phones and servers and encrypt all data, where just like low-tech keys, users give codes only to those they trust.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] In terms of regulation, there are few that address key storage in depth.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] "Some contain minimal guidance like 'don’t store keys with encrypted data' or suggest that 'keys should be kept securely.'" The notable exceptions to that are PCI DSS 3.2.1, NIST 800-53 and NIST 800–57.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] For optimal security, keys may be stored in a Hardware Security Module (HSM) or protected using technologies such as Trusted Execution Environment (TEE, e.g.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Intel SGX) or Multi-Party Computation (MPC).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Additional alternatives include utilizing Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), virtual HSMs, aka "Poor Man's Hardware Security Modules" (pmHSM), or non-volatile Field-Programmable-Gate-Arrays (FPGA) with supporting System-on-Chip configurations.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] In order to verify the integrity of a key stored without compromising its actual value a KCV algorithm can be used.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] The major issue is length of time a key is to be used, and therefore frequency of replacement.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Because it increases any attacker's required effort, keys should be frequently changed.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] This also limits loss of information, as the number of stored encrypted messages which will become readable when a key is found will decrease as the frequency of key change increases.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Historically, symmetric keys have been used for long periods in situations in which key exchange was very difficult or only possible intermittently.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Ideally, the symmetric key should change with each message or interaction, so that only that message will become readable if the key is learned (*e.g.*, stolen, cryptanalyzed, or social engineered).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Security: Vulnerability of keys from outside hackers, malicious insiders.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Availability: Ensuring data accessibility for authorized users.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Heterogeneity: Supporting multiple databases, applications and standards.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Governance: Defining policy-driven access control and protection for data.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Governance includes compliance with data protection requirements.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Key management compliance refers to the oversight, assurance, and capability of being able to demonstrate that keys are securely managed.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Compliance can be achieved with respect to national and international data protection standards and regulations, such as Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, Sarbanes–Oxley Act, or General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] A *key management system* (KMS), also known as a *cryptographic key management system* (CKMS) or *enterprise key management system* (EKMS), is an integrated approach for generating, distributing and managing cryptographic keys for devices and applications.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] They may cover all aspects of security - from the secure generation of keys over the secure exchange of keys up to secure key handling and storage on the client.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Thus, a KMS includes the backend functionality for key generation, distribution, and replacement as well as the client functionality for injecting keys, storing and managing keys on devices.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Many specific applications have developed their own key management systems with home grown protocols.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] However, as systems become more interconnected keys need to be shared between those different systems.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] To facilitate this, key management standards have evolved to define the protocols used to manage and exchange cryptographic keys and related information.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] KMIP is an extensible key management protocol that has been developed by many organizations working within the OASIS standards body.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] The first version was released in 2010, and it has been further developed by an active technical committee.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] The protocol allows for the creation of keys and their distribution among disparate software systems that need to utilize them.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] It covers the full key life cycle of both symmetric and asymmetric keys in a variety of formats, the wrapping of keys, provisioning schemes, and cryptographic operations as well as meta data associated with the keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] The protocol is backed by an extensive series of test cases, and interoperability testing is performed between compliant systems each year.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] A list of some 80 products that conform to the KMIP standard can be found on the OASIS website.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] The security policy of a key management system provides the rules that are to be used to protect keys and metadata that the key management system supports.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] This protection covers the complete key life-cycle from the time the key becomes operational to its elimination.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] A public-key infrastructure is a type of key management system that uses hierarchical digital certificates to provide authentication, and public keys to provide encryption.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] PKIs are used in World Wide Web traffic, commonly in the form of SSL and TLS.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Group key management means managing the keys in a group communication.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Most of the group communications use multicast communication so that if the message is sent once by the sender, it will be received by all the users.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] The main problem in multicast group communication is its security.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] In order to improve the security, various keys are given to the users.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] Using the keys, the users can encrypt their messages and send them secretly.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-management] IETF.org released RFC 4046, entitled Multicast Security (MSEC) Group Key Management Architecture, which discusses the challenges of group key management.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] In cryptography, **key wrap** constructions are a class of symmetric encryption algorithms designed to encapsulate (encrypt) cryptographic key material.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] The Key Wrap algorithms are intended for applications such as protecting keys while in untrusted storage or transmitting keys over untrusted communications networks.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] The constructions are typically built from standard primitives such as block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] Key Wrap may be considered as a form of key encapsulation algorithm, although it should not be confused with the more commonly known *asymmetric* (public-key) key encapsulation algorithms (e.g., PSEC-KEM).
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] Key Wrap algorithms can be used in a similar application: to securely transport a session key by encrypting it under a long-term encryption key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] In the late 1990s, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) posed the "Key Wrap" problem: to develop secure and efficient cipher-based key encryption algorithms.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] The resulting algorithms would be formally evaluated by NIST, and eventually approved for use in NIST-certified cryptographic modules.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] NIST did not precisely define the security goals of the resulting algorithm, and left further refinement to the algorithm developers.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] Goals (3) and (5) are particularly important, given that many widely deployed authenticated encryption algorithms (e.g., AES-CCM) are already sufficient to accomplish the remaining goals.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] Several constructions have been proposed.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] Each of the proposed algorithms can be considered as a form of authenticated encryption algorithm providing confidentiality for highly entropic messages such as cryptographic keys.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] The AES Key Wrap Specification, AESKW, TDKW, and AKW1 are intended to maintain confidentiality under adaptive chosen ciphertext attacks, while the AKW2 algorithm is designed to be secure only under known-plaintext (or weaker) attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] (The stated goal of AKW2 is for use in legacy systems and computationally limited devices where use of the other algorithms would be impractical.) AESKW, TDKW and AKW2 also provide the ability to authenticate cleartext "header", an associated block of data that is not encrypted.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] Rogaway and Shrimpton evaluated the design of the ANSX9.102 algorithms with respect to the stated security goals.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] Among their general findings, they noted the lack of clearly stated design goals for the algorithms, and the absence of security proofs for all constructions.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] In their paper, Rogaway and Shrimpton proposed a provable key-wrapping algorithm (SIV—the Synthetic Initialization Vector mode) that authenticates and encrypts an arbitrary string and authenticates, but does not encrypt, associated data which can be bound into the wrapped key.
[src:envelope-encryption/key-wrap] This has been specified as a new AES mode in RFC 5297.
